# Model ranking — spec 0.3 + hotfix vlp.1 (exclusion + tertiary tie-break).
#
# This file is an EXCLUSION list and a TERTIARY TIE-BREAK hint. It does
# NOT restrict which models the resolver considers. Unknown families are
# FIRST-CLASS candidates: a newly-launched tier above Fable wins
# automatically by recency, without an edit to this file.
#
# Syntax
# ------
# Lines starting with `!` are exclusions:
#
#     !claude-haiku       # drop every claude-haiku-* model
#
# Lines without `!` are family prefixes used to break ties when two
# surviving candidates have identical created_at AND max_input_tokens.
# Lines higher in the file get a lower (better) tie-break rank.
#
# Comments (`#`) and blank lines are ignored. Whitespace is trimmed.
#
# Resolver sort (primary -> tertiary)
# -----------------------------------
#   1. created_at DESC   — newest model wins (ISO 8601 from /v1/models).
#   2. max_input_tokens DESC — larger context wins on date tie.
#   3. ranking-file position ASC — families listed earlier preferred;
#      unknown families slot after every listed family for the tie-break.
#
# When the resolver picks a winner whose created_at is missing or
# unparseable, the SessionStart notice prints LOUDLY with the manual
# `/workflow-model <id>` adopt command and refuses to auto-rewrite the
# pins — so a malformed listing can never silently switch the workflow.
#
# Why this is set up as exclusion-only
# ------------------------------------
# Before hotfix vlp.1 this file was a strict allow-list: only families
# whose prefix appeared here could be selected, with version-tuple
# sorting inside each family. That meant a brand-new family tier shipped
# upstream (e.g. above Fable) would be invisible to the resolver until
# someone hand-edited this file. Reversing the polarity — exclusion +
# tie-break, with created_at as the primary sort — fixes principle 1
# ("auto-upgrade") without requiring this file to track upstream
# releases.
#
# Tier list (tertiary tie-break order; from best to worst when dates
# are identical):

# Tier 1: Fable family — Claude's most capable in-cycle model (per
# /docs/en/model-config: "the most capable model in Claude Code").
claude-fable

# Tier 2: Mythos family — Fable's stablemate per the Fable launch notes.
claude-mythos

# Tier 3: Opus family — current default for the Anthropic API on Max,
# Team Premium, Enterprise pay-as-you-go.
claude-opus

# Tier 4: Sonnet family — daily-coding default on Pro / Team Standard /
# Enterprise subscription seats.
claude-sonnet

# Tier 5: Haiku family — fast/cheap. Listed last so it loses every
# tie-break against the heavier tiers above. Add `!claude-haiku` (above
# the tier list) to exclude haiku entirely if you never want it picked
# even when it is the newest model in the listing.
claude-haiku
